    <div class="post-container" id="fpc-3127966">
                      
		<div class="post" id="post-3127966">
		<div class="long">
			<div class="head">
									<div class="options">
						<a href="javascript:;" onclick="togglePostFold(event,3127966)" class="btn btn-default btn-small btn-sm">Fold</a>
					</div>
								<div class="title" id="post-title-3127966">
																		
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/communism-will-win" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(617958); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=617958&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610227299" alt="Communism will win" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=617958)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/communism-will-win" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(617958); return false;" >Communism will win</a></span> <span class="odate time_1499436987 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">07 Jul 2017 14:16</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-3127966">
									

<p>This is a guide to <em>getting</em> feedback, not <em>giving</em> it. That's why I didn't bother to delineate between 'good' and 'bad' critique here, just whether an author should follow the advice they're given. Like, I would agree that proofreading is usually a secondary concern, and that reviewers should focus their efforts elsewhere&#8230; But at the same time, if someone does point out a typo, there's usually no reason for the author NOT to fix it.</p>
<p>The other bit mostly applies to like, sensitive or specialized subject matter, such as sexual assault or military matters. If someone is going overboard on a purely personal preference, or on some other misguided thing, they're liable to trip some of the &quot;don't follow this feedback&quot; signs.</p>

							</div>

										<div class="signature">
					<hr class="signature-separator"/>
					

<p>if your reading this your gay</p>

